e LOOKUP_LINK, to be passed by sys_linkat() when<br />&gt; resolving the target.<br /><br />[ .. snipped .. ]<br /><br />Yes. I think we should do this, but I think we should also look at<br />what _other_ LOOKUP_xyz we should do for the /proc case.<br /><br />For the read-only fd case, we should have a LOOKUP_WRITE flag, and<br />return -EPERM if an operation is a write, and we terminate in that<br />LAST_BIND case.<br /><br />That would catch the truncate() case, but also the "open a read-only<br />fd for write or O_TRUNC" case.<br /><br />Anything else? What other path operations matter that follow links<br />than truncate(), link() and open()?<br /><br />                Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
